g-C3N4, a planar two-dimensional sheet similar to graphene with tri-s-triazine ring as the basic structure, are synthesized by thermal polymerization of melamine [32]. It is regarded as a polymer semiconductor and is commonly used as a novel non-metallic photocatalytic material [33]. The typical layered structures are easily exfoliated into few-layered nanosheets as it combined by van der waals forces. In addition, its shear modulus is as high as 21.6 MPa, which expects to inhibit the Li dendrites growth [34]. The prepared bulk g-C3N4 powder was pale yellow in appearance and stacked in layers observed by scanning electron microscopy (SEM) (Fig. S1 a). The g-C3N4 nanosheets were well dispersed in tetrahydrofuran after ultrasonic peeling of bulk powder (Fig. S1 b). The exfoliated g-C3N4 nanosheets present folded layered micro-structure with ∼10 nm nanometers thick and about several microns in diameter as determined by transmission electron microscopy (TEM) and atomic force microscopy (AFM) (Figs. 2
a and S2). The FTIR analysis was carried out to identify the functional groups of g-C3N4 (Fig. 2 d), the characteristic peaks of three segments at 810, 1200–1700 and 3000–3300 cm−1 could be assigned to the breathing of tri-s-triazine units, the stretching of CN heterocycles and string vibration amino (N-H) groups in g-C3N4, respectively [30]. Notably, XPS reveals that ∼53 at% of nitrogen was detected in the g-C3N4 (Fig. 2 e). The abundant nitrogen species is typically regulates the Li plating/stripping behavior through interactions with Li ions [31]. Li-GCN is obtained by immersing the fresh Li foil inside into the THF suspension containing a few layers of g-C3N4 nanosheets. It can be seen from Fig. 2 b, the surface morphology of Li-GCN looks coarse, the increased specific surface area may facilitate adequate contact of the interface. Combined with energy dispersive spectrum (EDS) mapping which displays the C and N elements are evenly distributed on the surface of Li-GCN. It can be revealed that g-C3N4 nanosheets have been uniformly coated on the lithium foil surface. The AFM images of bare Li and Li-GCN present a smooth and uniform surface without aggregates ( Fig. 2 c and Fig. S3
).
